So, I just came back from a very intense summer. Over the past 12 months, I've traveled and lived with some of my closest friends. I've had someone in my close vicinity almost at all times. 

Obviously, living with your friends is one of the greatest things, but at the same time, you don't really get to exist by yourself. There's always someone nearby who can distract you or help you out. This is great, but you kind of forget how to be in solitude because of it. That's why I wanted to talk about the importance of solitude and being by yourself in this entry.

![][image1]

### Recognizing Companionship

Don't get me wrong---always having someone to bounce ideas or difficulties off of, or to come to in a time of need, is amazing. But it can also create a sense of reliance. For me, at least, it sometimes prevents me from exploring certain avenues of thought. 

Of course, new avenues open up when I have someone around because we work together, and that should definitely be recognized. However, there are some thoughts that come to me only after a couple of days of being by myself, whether in a new place or even a familiar one.

### Spending Time In Solitude is Dating Yourself

Back to the topic of spending time alone---it's a valuable opportunity to learn about yourself. I think when you leave home or don't necessarily have a roommate for the first time, it's just you, and you have to take care of yourself. I think it's important to see this as a positive thing. At least for me, I try to, because after being with someone for so long, it's refreshing. The fact that it's a change makes it a challenge and I think develops me.

### "If you're lonely when you're alone, you're in bad company." ? Jean-Paul Sartre

The idea of treating yourself as you would any other person is very important, I think, and something that's a core value of mine. You should treat yourself just as you would treat a close friend that you want to take care of. This applies not only to your body and physical needs but also to your emotional and mental health. It means emotionally regulating yourself and taking care of your mental well-being. For example, getting yourself out of bed when you would tell a friend to do the same, and maybe going for a walk in the park.

### Take Care of Yourself

For me, I wake up two or three hours before sunset (due to circumstances I can explain later). Since sunlight is so important after my first hour of waking up---brushing my teeth, breakfast, and all that---I try to take myself to the park to do some work. It's also important to take yourself out on dates and do the things you appreciate, whether that's a museum in my case, or exploring a new part of town, or maybe eating good food for the case of others. By being with yourself, you can learn more about who you are, what things you like, what attracts you, and what doesn't really interest you. For me, weirdly enough, eating the best high-quality food is not my priority. Not that I don't appreciate it, but I get significant, meaningful joy from eating food that's just okay. 

When you're constantly surrounded by friends or family, especially if you're more on the listening side than the talking side like I am, it can be harder for your own ideas to be heard. So, take a moment and think: what ideas do you hold?
